      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The pH level of the dough can indeed affect the Maillard reaction, and it's a fascinating aspect of the chemistry involved. You see, the Maillard reaction is a redox reaction, meaning it involves the transfer of electrons between molecules. The pH level of the environment can influence the availability of these electrons, which in turn affects the rate and extent of the reaction.\n\nIn general, a more acidic environment (lower pH) favors the formation of certain Maillard reaction products, while a more alkaline environment (higher pH) favors the formation of others. This is because the pH level affects the ionization state of the amino acids and reducing sugars, which in turn affects their reactivity.\n\nFor example, asparagine, one of the key amino acids involved in the Maillard reaction, is more ionized in an alkaline environment, making it less reactive. On the other hand, in an acidic environment, asparagine is less ionized, making it more reactive.\n\nLemon juice, being acidic, can indeed influence the Maillard reaction in your dough. The citric acid in lemon juice can lower the pH of the dough, favoring the formation of certain Maillard reaction products. This can result in a more intense, darker brown",
